Project Story
Motivation

I wanted to build a smart litter box monitoring system that could automatically track a cat's litter box usage and help identify potential health issues.

The initial idea was simple:

Detect when a cat enters the litter box
Take photos automatically
Analyze the litter box contents using AI

However, during development I encountered several practical engineering challenges that required multiple design iterations.

Iteration 1: Basic Photo Capture System

The first prototype simply captured an image whenever a litter box event occurred.

Problems

This approach generated many false records:

Empty litter box images
Camera noise
Sensor misfires
Repeated captures of the same scene

As a result, visit counts became unreliable and AI analysis was frequently performed on irrelevant images.

Lessons Learned

A trigger alone is not sufficient.

The system must first verify that a cat is actually present before recording an event.

Iteration 2: YOLO-Based Cat Verification

To reduce false positives, YOLOv8 was integrated into the system.

Improvement

Instead of immediately recording a visit:

Capture an entry image
Run YOLO detection
Verify that a cat exists in the frame
Record the visit only if a cat is detected
Result

This significantly reduced false records and improved the reliability of litter box statistics.

Iteration 3: Duplicate Image Filtering

After extended testing, another issue appeared.

Many captured images were nearly identical.

Examples:

Cat remains stationary
Camera view unchanged
Multiple captures of the same litter box condition
Improvement

Image similarity comparison was added using:

Histogram comparison
Pixel difference analysis

Images exceeding a similarity threshold are automatically discarded.

Result

Storage requirements were reduced and unnecessary AI requests were avoided.

Iteration 4: AI Waste Analysis

The next goal was to understand what was inside the litter box.

Google Gemini Vision was integrated to analyze captured images.

Problems

The AI occasionally assumed that every image contained waste because the image came from a litter box system.

Improvement

Prompt engineering was introduced.

The model is explicitly instructed to:

Determine whether waste is actually present
Identify non-waste objects
Report uncertainty when visibility is poor
Avoid making unsupported assumptions
Result

More reliable and interpretable analysis reports.

Iteration 5: Health Trend Monitoring

Single litter box visits provide limited information.

A cat's health is often reflected in long-term behavioral changes.

Improvement

A local statistics engine was developed to store:

Visit frequency
Visit duration
Daily activity history

The system computes:

24-hour activity summaries
7-day health trends
Long-term behavior changes
Result

The system evolved from event monitoring to behavioral monitoring.

Iteration 6: Startup Optimization

As more AI features were added, startup time increased significantly.

Investigation revealed that YOLO was being loaded during program initialization.

Problems
Slow startup
Web dashboard unavailable during model loading
Poor user experience
Improvement

Several optimizations were introduced:

Lazy YOLO loading
Background model preloading
Faster web server initialization
Optional simulation mode
Result

The dashboard becomes available almost immediately while AI models continue loading in the background.

Key Engineering Takeaways

This project evolved from a simple camera-based prototype into a multi-stage AI monitoring system.

The most important lesson was that building a reliable system required much more than simply connecting a camera to an AI model.

Each iteration introduced new challenges involving:

Computer vision
Data quality
AI reliability
System performance
User experience

The final system reflects a continuous engineering process of identifying limitations, testing solutions, and refining the design.
